tain of the 1st century  ad  in the Latinized form <i>Caractacus</i>, son of Cunobelinos."],"variants":[]},{"name":"ap","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Short form of any of the names beginning with this syllable."],"variants":[{"name":"Alexander","meanings":["From the Latin form of the Greek name <i>Alexandros</i>, from <i>alexein</i> ‘to defend’ + <i>anēr</i> ‘man, warrior’ (genitive <i>andros</i>). The name became extremely popular in the post-classical period, and was borne by several individuals in the New Testament and some early Christian saints. Its use as a common given name throughout Europe, however, derives largely from the fame of  Alexander the Great , King of Macedon (  356–323  bc  ), around whom a large body of popular legend grew up in late antiquity, much of which came to be embodied in the medieval ‘Alexander romances’."]},{"name":"Alan","meanings":["Of Celtic origin and uncertain derivation (possibly a diminutive of a word meaning ‘rock’). It was introduced into England by  Breton  followers of  William the Conqueror , most notably  Alan , Earl of Brittany, who was rewarded for his services with vast estates in the newly conquered kingdom. In Britain the variants  <b>Allan</b>  and  <b>Allen</b>  are considerably less frequent, and generally represent transferred uses of surname forms, whereas in America all three forms of the name are approximately equally common.  See also  Alun ."]},{"name":"Albert","meanings":["From an Old French name, <i>Albert</i>, of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>adal</i> ‘noble’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’. This was adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to England, displacing the Old English form <i>Æþelbeorht</i>. The name is popular in a variety of forms in Western Europe, and has been traditional in a number of European princely families. It was out of favour in England for centuries, however, and the revival of its popularity in the 19th century was largely in honour of  Queen Victoria's  consort,  Prince Albert of Saxe-Coburg-Gotha ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Caradoc ap Einion was born about 1070, in Glamorgan, Wales, United Kingdom, his father, Einion ap Collwyn, was 51 and his mother, Lucy verch Iestyn, was 29. He had at least 1 son with Gladys Tudor."},"et":{"about 1070–":"umbes 1070–Surnud","1070–Male":"1070–Surnud","1090–Male":"1090–Surnud","1100–Female":"1100–Surnud","1102–Female":"1102–Surnud","1130–Male":"1130–Surnud","1132–Male":"1132–Surnud","1070–Female":"1070–Surnud","–Female":"Surnud","1145–1207":"1145–1207","1120–Male":"1120–Surnud","1130–Female":"1130–Surnud","1021–1100":"1021–1100","1043–Female":"1043–Surnud","1090":"1090","about 1070":"umbes 1070","1132":"1132","1043":"1043","1021":"1021","1120":"1120","1130":"1130","abt 1145":"umbes 1145","1070":"1070","Abt 1130":"umbes 1130","1102":"1102","about 1963":"umbes 1963","1145":"1145","1100":"1100","about 1120":"umbes 1120","1207":"1207","Senghenydd, Glamorgan, Wales":"Senghenydd, Glamorgan, Wales","Senghennydd, Glamorganshire, Wales":"Glamorgan, Wales, United Kingdom","Glamorgan Co., Wales":"Glamorgan, Wales, United Kingdom","Wales":"Wales","Senghenydel,,, Wales":"Wales, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"about 1070–":"noin 1070–Kuollut","1070–Male":"1070–Kuollut","1090–Male":"1090–Kuollut","1100–Female":"1100–Kuollut","1102–Female":"1102–Kuollut","1130–Male":"1130–Kuollut","1132–Male":"1132–Kuollut","1070–Female":"1070–Kuollut","–Female":"Kuollut","1145–1207":"1145–1207","1120–Male":"1120–Kuollut","1130–Female":"1130–Kuollut","1021–1100":"1021–1100","1043–Female":"1043–Kuollut","1090":"1090","about 1070":"noin 1070","1132":"1132","1043":"1043","1021":"1021","1120":"1120","1130":"1130","abt 1145":"noin 1145","1070":"1070","Abt 1130":"noin 1130","1102":"1102","about 1963":"noin 1963","1145":"1145","1100":"1100","about 1120":"noin 1120","1207":"1207","Senghenydd, Glamorgan, Wales":"Senghenydd, Glamorgan, Wales","S